Provide an introduction to the R programming Package caret used in predictive modeling.



Post Outline:

  1. caret Package overview.

  2. Demonstrate caret package using a Classification example using Cell segmentation dataset.


caret Package overview.


    The basics
  • The caret package contains a set of functions used in the complex regression and classification model training problems.

  • caret stands for Classification and REgression Training

  • caret package utilizes up to 32 packages but only loads packages as needed, or prompts the user to install it

  • The main package tools include:
    • Data Splitting
    • Pre-Processing
    • Feature Selection
    • Model Tuning Using Resampling
    • Variable Importance Estimation

  • One of the primary tools is the train function that is used to
    • Evaluates the effect of model tuning parameters on the performance by using resampling.
    • Chooses the optional model across the parameters.
    • Provides model performance estimates from the training set.

  • caret is powerful package as almost every step of the process can be customized.


Demonstrate caret package using a Classification example using Cell segmentation dataset.


    The data and objective
  • The data is provided by and consist of measurements taken from individual cells using a high content screen for cancer.

  • The data consists of 2019 rows and 116 columns. Each row is an instance and the 116 are features/measurements taken for each cell.

  • The objective is to use predictive modeling to examine cell characteristics in order to understand the effects of disease on the size, shape and characteristics of cells.

  • In the example below, a classification predictive model using caret will be used to classify cells as either poorly segmented or well-segmented.

Calculate the cumulative percentage of variance which each component¶

  • The standard deviations for the columns in the data are stored in pcaObject and divide by the sum of the squared standard deviation
  • Step 1 is the percent variance
  • Step 2 is the cumulative percent variance

Use the caret class preProcess¶

  • Transform, center, scale, or impute values,
  • Performs the spatial sign transformation and feature extraction.
  • preProcess also calculates the required quantities for the transformation.
  • The function applies the predict method which perform Box–Cox transform, center, and scale the data
  • preProcess then performed the PCA
In [24]:
trans <- preProcess(segDataCont, method = c("BoxCox", "center", "scale", "pca"))  ## need {caret} package
trans

Filtering Data¶

  • Step is to filter for near-zero variance predictors
  • the caret package function nearZeroVar returns the column numbers of any predictors nearZeroVar(
  • this pre-processing set should not be performed on continous predictors
  • Only categorical

Filter data based on correlations using the findCorrelation function¶

  • findCorrelation function applies an algorithm with a given threshold of pairwise correlations
  • returns the index of the columns denoting the predictors that are recommended for filtering/deletion
